The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylous forms may be an artifact of their study in slabbed outcrops, since both groups were primarily littoral creatures with small unfused vertebrae.
